<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-521-769  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 521 769.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Government sues to recover confidential data sold for $45.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of JusticeCourt CasesGovernment AgencyConfidentialityLegal IssuesPurchasesComputer Systems.andO;Person:    Hayes, Charles (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GOVERNMENT SUES TO RECOVER CONFIDENTIAL DATA SOLD FOR $45 PIKEVILLE,KENTUCKY, U.S.A., 1990 SEP 3 (NB) -- A hearing has been set for September 4to consider the U.S.andP;  Justice Department's suit against Charles Hayes for therecovery of confidential data contained within a computer system purchased byHayes for $45.andP;  U.S.andP;  District Judge Eugene Silver, Jr., within hours of thefiling of the suit on August 30, ordered Hayes to immediately return thecomputer system to the government and not examine, copy or distribute thedata.andM;Hayes, who sells surplus government equipment, bought the system and thenresold it.andP;  The documents filed by the Justice Deptartment say that atechnician failed to erase the memory of the computer at the U.S.andP;  Attorney'soffice in Lexington before the government sold the system in July to Hayes.andO;The documents further say that the computer's memory and backup storage tapescontain sensitive details about FBI informants, federally protectedwitnesses, sealed indictments and personal information about employees inU.S.andP;  Attorney Louis DeFalaise's office.andM;The system, manufactured by Harris-Lanier Corporation, contains 13 computerterminals, two central memory units with 93 megabytes of memory, twocartridge module drives and nine printers.andP;  It has the capacity for  storinghundreds of thousands of pages.andP;  Hayes bid $45 in July for the system andpicked it up on August 3.andP;  In the interim, the memory was supposed to beerased but, after Hayes picked up the computer, the Harris- Lanier techniciantold government officials he didn't erase the memory after all.andP;  Due to thebroken state of the equipment, normal computer commands could not be used toerase the data and a magnetic probe that had been used to scramble the datawas said to be too weak.andP;  The lawsuit alleges that &quot;the information almostcertainly remained stored within some parts of the computer equipment.&quot; Italso contends that Hayes, with the help of his computer technician JimFreeman, can retrieve the data.andM;Wire services quote Hayes as saying that FBI agents who visited his businessAugust 17 treated him rudely and departed after a bitter exchange when theyattempted to examine his office without a search warrant.andP;  Hayes was alsoquoted as denying that he looked at the information, The Justice Department,in the lawsuit, alleges that Hayes hasn't been fothcoming.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900902)</TEXT></DOC>